A deHavilland DHC-8-100 aircraft struck a flock of geese during takeoff.
The accident occurred on August 10, 2014 at about 0605 eastern daylight time.
The accident occurred at Middletown Harrisburg International Airport (KMDT) in Harrisburg, Pennsylvania.
The aircraft registration was N815EX.
The aircraft was operated by Piedmont Airlines.
Piedmont Airlines was doing business as USAirways Express.
The flight number was 4206.
The flight was operating under 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 121.
The flight was a regularly scheduled passenger flight.
The flight was scheduled to travel from Harrisburg International Airport to Philadelphia International Airport.
Philadelphia International Airport is located in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
Philadelphia International Airport's code is KPHL.
The aircraft sustained substantial damage.
There were no injuries to passengers or crew.
There were 20 people on board the aircraft.
The captain was the pilot flying.
The first officer was the pilot monitoring.
About 15 seconds into the takeoff roll, the captain observed a large group of geese flying from right to left in front of the airplane.
The captain observed the geese prior to reaching V1 speed.
The captain immediately initiated a rejected takeoff.
The airplane impacted multiple geese on the front windshield.
The airplane impacted multiple geese on the right engine propeller.
The impact caused a severe vibration.
The flight crew shut down the right engine as the airplane slowed.
The flight crew returned the aircraft to the gate.
Examination of the airplane indicated damage to the right propeller.
Examination of the airplane indicated a broken passenger window.
Examination of the airplane indicated damage to the fuselage skin.
Examination of the airplane indicated damage to the stringers near the broken window.
The National Transportation Safety Board determined the probable cause of the accident to be the airplane's collision with geese during the takeoff roll.

text:
# Aviation Investigation Final Report

## Location:
Harrisburg, Pennsylvania

## Date & Time: 
August 10, 2014, 06:05 Local

## Aircraft:
DEHAVILLAND DHC 8 102

## Defining Event:
Birdstrike

## Flight Conducted Under:
Part 121: Air carrier - Scheduled

## Accident Number:
DCA14CA147

## Registration:
N815EX

## Aircraft Damage:
Substantial

## Injuries:
20 None

## Analysis

On August 10, 2014 at about 0605 eastern daylight time, a deHavilland DHC-8-100, N815EX, operated by Piedmont Airlines d.b.a. USAirways Express flight 4206, struck a flock of geese during the takeoff roll from Middletown Harrisburg International Airport (KMDT), Harrisburg, Pennsylvania. There were no injuries to the passengers or crew and the airplane sustained damage. The flight was operating under the provisions of 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 121 as a regularly scheduled passenger flight between KMDT and Philadelphia International Airport (KPHL), Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.

The captain was the pilot flying and the first officer was the pilot monitoring. According to the flight crew, about 15 seconds into the takeoff roll and prior to V1, the captain observed a large group of geese flying from right to left in front of the airplane. He immediately initiated a rejected takeoff as the airplane impacted multiple geese on the front windshield and the right engine propeller, which caused a severe vibration. The flight crew shut down the right engine as the airplane slowed and returned to the gate.

Examination of the airplane indicated damage to the right propeller, a broken passenger window, and damage to the fuselage skin and stringers near the broken window.

## Probable Cause and Findings

The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident to be: the airplanes collision with geese during the takeoff roll.
